# The Negotiator — Auto Glass Quote & Negotiation Agent

Built for the Hack-Nation / MIT hackathon (ElevenLabs-sponsored "The Negotiator" challenge).

An AI system that calls multiple auto glass shops, gets itemized quotes over the phone, negotiates using only verified facts (never bluffs), and hands back a ranked, cited recommendation. The vertical is windshield repair/replacement, chosen because pricing is opaque, ADAS camera recalibration is a common hidden fee, and quotes are only ever given by phone.

## What it does

1. **Estimator (intake)** — takes a fixed job spec (vehicle, damage, ADAS camera presence, ZIP, payment preference) and freezes it into a hash so every shop is quoted against the identical job.
2. **Caller (quote collection)** — a voice agent calls three shops with distinct negotiation styles (premium chain, independent lowballer, mobile-only operator), extracts itemized line items and a confirmed all-in total, and logs everything with a transcript citation.
3. **Closer (negotiation + ranking)** — the same voice agent calls back the best comparable shop, negotiates using a "verified leverage" mechanism (it can only cite a competing offer if that fact was actually reconciled from a real transcript), then ranks all quotes on price, completeness, scope, schedule, and terms — with red flags for omitted calibration fees, suspicious lowballing, and total mismatches.

The core design principle is **policy-heavy, model-light**: all money math, red-flag detection, leverage verification, and ranking happen in deterministic TypeScript (`policy.ts`). The LLM only ever handles conversation and prose — it cannot invent a number or a competing offer that wasn't actually verified.

## Repo structure

| Path | What it is |
|---|---|
| `config.ts` | The fixed demo job spec (2021 VW Tiguan, front ADAS camera, ZIP 28202, cash) and its frozen hash |
| `domain.ts` | Zod schemas for every data type (quotes, outcomes, verified facts, policy decisions, recommendations) |
| `policy.ts` | Deterministic logic: leverage verification, red flags, ranking, spec hashing |
| `negotiation-playbook.yaml` | Named negotiation tactics grounded in real negotiation theory, with an explicit list of forbidden manipulative tactics |
| `playbook.ts` | Loads the playbook and filters tactics by what's actually authorized for a given call |
| `persona.*.yaml` | The three shop personas the system negotiates against (economics, concession rules, refusal triggers) |
| `prompts.ts` | The actual ElevenLabs agent prompt — **one buyer agent**, driven by a `{{phase}}` dynamic variable (`QUOTE_COLLECTION` vs `NEGOTIATION`), not two separate agents |
| `tools.ts` | Implementations of the 8 webhook tools the agent calls during a conversation (log items, request leverage, close call, etc.) |
| `store.ts` | File-based JSON persistence for a run (`.data/current-run.json`, owner-only permissions) |
| `server.ts` | Fastify server: tool endpoints + ElevenLabs post-call webhook (HMAC-verified) |
| `textloop.ts` | Text-only closed-loop simulation of a full run (no phone calls) — runs all 3 personas, negotiates, ranks, and gate-checks the result |
| `scripts/provision-agents.ts` | Creates/updates the ElevenLabs agents (buyer + 3 personas) and their webhook tools via the API |
| `scripts/run-call.ts` | Places a real outbound call via Twilio/ElevenLabs for one persona/phase, or `--all` for a full quote-and-negotiate run |
| `auto-deal-navigator/` | React/TanStack Start frontend (quote comparison, negotiation view, recommendation, call log) — reads live data from `GET /runs/current`, falls back to mock data if no backend is set |
| `research/` | Team deep-dive docs on vertical selection (windshield, junk removal, catering) and architecture notes |

## Running it

**Text-only simulation (no ElevenLabs/Twilio needed):**
```
npm install
cp .env.example .env   # fill in OPENAI_API_KEY at minimum
npm start               # runs textloop.ts — full 3-shop quote + negotiate + rank + gate check
```

**Real phone calls:**
```
npm run server           # Fastify server, exposes /tools/* and /webhooks/elevenlabs
# expose it publicly, e.g.:
ngrok http 3000          # set PUBLIC_BASE_URL to the ngrok URL in .env
npm run provision        # creates/updates the ElevenLabs agents + tools
npm run call -- --persona premium_chain --phase QUOTE_COLLECTION --to +1XXXXXXXXXX
npm run call:all         # calls all 3 shops, then calls back the best one to negotiate
```

Required env vars (see `.env.example`): `OPENAI_API_KEY`, `ELEVENLABS_API_KEY`, `ELEVENLABS_PHONE_NUMBER_ID`, `TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID`, `TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN`, `TOOL_SHARED_SECRET`, `PUBLIC_BASE_URL`, `ELEVENLABS_WEBHOOK_SECRET`.

**Frontend:**
```
cd auto-deal-navigator
npm install
npm run dev
```

**Tests:**
```
npm test         # vitest
npm run typecheck
```

## The honesty mechanism

The buyer agent is never allowed to claim a competing offer from memory or invention. Before making any competitive claim it must call `request_leverage`, which is denied unless a `VerifiedFact` exists — minted only from a quote that was reconciled against the same frozen job spec and hasn't expired. The agent may only speak back the exact `allowedClaim` string the tool returns. Max 3 concession rounds per call. Forbidden tactics (fake urgency, invented competing bids, bluffed walkaways, guilt/pressure) are hard-excluded in the playbook, not just discouraged.

